INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("52", "2", "2016-08-04 10:33:52", "2016-08-04 10:33:52", "<strong>It all started with one simple question</strong>\r\n\r\nPhotography business was booming for Jesse Lake. A professional photographer for over ten years, he had helped hundreds of couples capture the most special day in their lives. He had earned a reputation among the locals and his photography business gained a lot of popularity. On this particular day, a female client by the name of Judith Praise walked into his office door accompanied by a muscular man with a mustache. Their wedding was around the corner and they needed a professional photographer for the day. She had been referred to Jesse by a friend and was optimistic his company was the perfect choice for her big day. After exchanging a few pleasantries, the routine consultation was underway. It all started with a simple question; which is the most suitable day for the video shoot? She also asked for professional advice on the best locations in town for photo-shoots and general advice on the day itself. Lake carefully noted the questions down and answered them to the best of his ability. He gave his professional advice to the best of his ability. This was his bread and butter and he did it with passion. He advised Judith and Marcel on a few good locations around town and suggested they take a reconnaissance tour of the spots before the wedding date. On the suitable day for the wedding video shooting, Jesse managed to convince Judith and Marcel to hold their wedding on Saturday. They agreed on the date, the total cost of the shooting and signed down the contract. After exchanging a few more extra words, Judith and Marcel were on their way. They left Jesse thinking about wedding and the preparations he needed to make. He was used to such scenarios and in the back of his mind he already envisioned a successful day at work come the wedding day. Little did he know that his decisions would come to haunt him later!\r\n\r\n<strong>The Perfect Day</strong>\r\n\r\nTwo weeks later, and Saturday was here! Jesse had made all the necessary preparations and he felt everything was on the right track. After assembling all the essentials for the photo-shoot, he, together with his two cameramen set out to the bride\'s house as agreed. The weather in the morning looked great and Jess was convinced that this was the perfect day for the shoot. As earlier recommended, Jess was supposed to start the video shoot at the brides home while two of his assistants worked in the grooms home. The first few shots and videos in the morning were just perfect. The sun was all out and the mood was awesome. All over a sudden, it started looking cloudy and from a distance one could sense that torrential rains were coming. By the time the bridal party was getting to the photo-shoot spot that Jess had recommended, it was already drizzling and the clouds cast a gloomy shadow over the park making the video shoot so difficult. The park was not only muddy but had way too many trees which made it look so dark. Inside the cathedral, things were not any better. All the photos and videos looked really dark and the overall quality was so poor that the client ended up suing Luke. She claimed that the advice that Jess had given them greatly affected their decision to hold the wedding on Saturday. Judith claimed that he had misled her with faulty decisions and unprofessional advice. Right from the recommended date itself, suggested the photo-shoot locations to the quality of the videos produced everything seemed to work against Jess\r\n\r\n<strong>Without protection: where did Jess go wrong?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe legal suit filed against Jess and his business took a great toll on him and his business. He spent thousands of dollars hiring a lawyer to help him argue his case. He spent weeks in the courtroom and could not run his business during this time. He was still shocked that the client had sued him. Look, offering professional advice and recommendations was part of his business. He actually offered it as a bonus incentive and hardly charged a dime for the advice he gave out. All his previous clients had actually ended up tipping him handsomely after the advice he gave worked out great for them. He was still in shock that his free advice was threatening to bring his business down on its knees. A business he had toiled and moiled to set up for the last ten year. Six months in and out of the courtroom finally took their toll on Jesses photography business. He was ordered to pay a large sum of compensation fee to Judith and Marcel and ended up bankrupt. Its at this point that he started regretting not having insured his photography business. He realized that without proper insurance, he was open to unwarranted suits by clients for even the smallest of reasons. Too bad, it was a little too late. Lack of insurance had seen him run bankrupt and lose his fortune.\r\n\r\n<strong>Professional Liability Insurance Could have saved Jesse and a thousand other photographers across the country</strong>\r\n\r\nSo, having have read the devastating story of Jesse and his downfall, what could he have done differently? Could a professional liability insurance saved our friend Jesss business? The answer is yes. A professional liability insurance would have made all the difference. So why exactly is professional Liability Insurance important? Why should every photography business get this cover?\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Professional Liability Insurance Cover protects your photography business\r\nagainst errors and omissions, actual or alleged, which occur while providing your\r\nprofessional services. Lets take our friend Jesse as an example, had he been under insurance coverage, he would not have been sued for giving inaccurate advice or recommendations. This means that you can freely advise your clients without the fear that your recommendations and suggestions would work against you.</li>\r\n 	<li>Liability cover protects you if you fail to deliver a service or delayed delivery of a service. Sometimes even after signing a contract with a client, it is not possible to turn up to deliver the service. Sometimes you are just a few minutes late. Without cover, you are at risk of being sued and paying compensation fines</li>\r\n 	<li>Professional Liability Insurance protects you against third party claims arising from services offered by your employers, temporarily hired assistants and independent contractors. This means that every member affiliated to your business is given cover when offering professional services for you or on your behalf.</li>\r\n 	<li>Accidents and injuries that arise when you are offering professional photography services area also covered. Damages to your protect or bodily injuries that arise from working in the field are duly taken care of.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nClearly, if you own a photography agency or run a photography business, Professional Liability Insurance Cover is an absolute necessity. Owing to the unpredictable nature of this business, you should not take chances. Always be protected. Be smart, dont be like Jesse. Get a professional Liability Insurance Cover today!", "The Cost of Advice: How Photographer Jesse Lake Went Bankrupt", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "cost-advice-photographer-jesse-lake-went-bankrupt", "", "", "2016-08-04 10:33:52", "2016-08-04 10:33:52", "", "0", "http://nextinsurance.wpengine.com/?p=52", "0", "post", "", "0");
